Treat the functional-analytic proof the way one treats a linear map on a finite-dimensional space: first understand it on a manageable spanning piece, then extend from structure rather than coordinates.
Concretely, choose a dense subspace of simple vectors/functions, prove the desired estimate or identity there as if it were a matrix calculation, and make sure the constants are uniform.
Then pass to the whole space by continuity, completeness, weak compactness, or a density argument, exactly as a basis computation in finite dimensions determines the operator everywhere.
